<p><strong>Q: What is the First Law of Thermodynamics?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> The First Law states that energy can neither be created nor destroyed, only transferred or transformed. In other words, the total energy of a system and its surroundings remains constant.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Explain the concept of entropy.</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> Entropy is a measure of disorder in a system. As a system becomes more disordered, its entropy increases. Entropy is a key factor in determining the direction and efficiency of many processes.</p>
<p><strong>Q: What is the Gibbs Free Energy?</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> The Gibbs Free Energy is a thermodynamic potential that combines enthalpy with entropy. It is used to calculate the maximum amount of work that can be extracted from a system.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Describe the application of thermodynamics in power plants.</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> Thermodynamics is essential for understanding and optimizing power plant operations. By applying thermodynamic principles, engineers can design and operate plants that convert fuel into electricity efficiently and with minimal environmental impact.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Explain the role of thermodynamics in refrigeration.</strong></p>
<p><strong>A:</strong> Thermodynamics plays a crucial role in refrigeration systems. It helps engineers determine the optimal refrigerant, compressor, and expansion valve to create a system that efficiently removes heat from a confined space.</p>